{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Elene*, the moment occurs toward the end of the poem's single chapter. Having unearthed three crosses from Golgotha (Calvary), Judas cannot identify which is the True Cross (the \"victory-beacon\" or \"Rood\" on which Christ was crucified). The crosses are placed in the city center. At the ninth hour, a crowd brings a dead youth on a bier. Judas tests the crosses one by one over the corpse: the first two have no effect, but when the third—the True Cross—is raised over the body, the youth immediately rises to life, \"with spirit endowed, together both body and soul.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).",
